SIMPLE: demy
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Demy
<hw>De*my"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Demies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[See <er>Demi-</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A printing and a writing paper of particular sizes. See
under <er>Paper</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A half fellow at Magdalen College, Oxford.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>demi</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was elected into Magdalen College as a <qex>demy</qex>; a term
by which that society denominates those elsewhere called
⟦ldquo⟧scholars,⟦rdquo⟧ young men who partake of the founder's
benefaction, and succeed in their order to vacant fellowships.</q>
<rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Demy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Demy
<hw>De*my"</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to, or made of, the size
of paper called <xex>demy</xex>; <as>as, a <ex>demy</ex>
book</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>demythologisation</ent>⟦br⟧
